    "# The Visualisation Product\n",
    "\n",
    "## Structure — From Overview to Detail\n",
    "\n",
    "The report is divided into **five sections**, supporting both quick orientation and deeper exploration:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Section | Content | Primary user |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Overview** | KPI cards, headline totals | Marcus (management) |\n",
    "| **Trends** | Incident count and severity over 2015–2024 | Both |\n",
    "| **Countries & Industries** | Frequency and severity comparisons | Both |\n",
    "| **Threat Profiles** | Attack types, vulnerabilities, attack sources | Sophia (analyst) |\n",
    "| **Defense & Outcomes** | Defense mechanisms vs. resolution time and loss | Sophia (analyst) |\n",
    "\n",
    "## Overview Section — Immediate Orientation\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "**KPI cards** at the top of the page:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Total incidents recorded\n",
    "- Average financial loss (M$)\n",
    "- Average resolution time (h)\n",
    "- Most frequent attack type\n",
    "\n",
    "**Year trend sparkline** below the cards for immediate temporal context\n",
    "\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "**Why?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Addresses Marcus's need for a **fast entry point**\n",
    "- Answers \"how big is the problem overall?\" before any filtering\n",
    "- KPI cards are a familiar management communication format\n",
    "- Sets scale before comparative charts appear\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Trends Section — Temporal Patterns\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "**Line charts** across 2015–2024 for:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Incident count per year\n",
    "- Average financial loss per year\n",
    "- Average affected users per year\n",
    "- Average resolution time per year\n",
    "\n",
    "**Metric toggle** to switch between severity dimensions\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "**Why line charts?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Time series data maps naturally to lines\n",
    "- Allows users to see whether threats are growing, stable, or declining\n",
    "- Metric toggle avoids chart overload while keeping all severity dimensions accessible\n",
    "- Directly answers the first research question from the project charta\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Countries & Industries — Comparative Views\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "**Sorted bar charts** for country and industry comparisons:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Switchable metric: count / financial loss / affected users / resolution time\n",
    "- Sorted by selected metric so ranking is immediately visible\n",
    "\n",
    "**Grouped bar chart** for side-by-side severity comparison across countries\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "**Why sorted bars instead of a map?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Dataset contains only 10 countries — precise comparison matters more than geography\n",
    "- Sorted bars make ranking unambiguous\n",
    "- A choropleth would waste space and add visual complexity without analytical gain\n",
    "- Directly addresses Marcus's question: *\"Which industries face the greatest losses?\"*\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Threat Profiles — Attack and Vulnerability Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "**Heatmaps** for cross-category concentration:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Attack type × industry\n",
    "- Vulnerability type × industry\n",
    "- Attack source × country\n",
    "\n",
    "**Sorted bar charts** for attack type frequency and severity rankings\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "**Why heatmaps here?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Heatmaps efficiently show concentration patterns across two categorical dimensions simultaneously\n",
    "- Enables Sophia to answer: *\"Which vulnerability types are most common in Banking?\"*\n",
    "- Colour intensity encodes frequency or severity without requiring separate charts per combination\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Defense & Outcomes — Do Defenses Make a Difference?\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"55%\"}\n",
    "**Box plots** comparing:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Financial loss distribution by defense mechanism\n",
    "- Resolution time distribution by defense mechanism\n",
    "- Affected users distribution by defense mechanism\n",
    "\n",
    "Sorted by median value for easy ranking\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"45%\"}\n",
    "**Why box plots?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Distributions reveal spread and outliers — not just averages\n",
    "- Avoids misleading summary statistics when underlying distributions are wide\n",
    "- Enables Sophia to assess whether mechanisms like AI-based Detection or MFA are genuinely associated with better outcomes\n",
    "- Supports evidence-based recommendations without causal overclaiming\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Design Decisions Summary {.smaller}\n",
    "\n",
    "| Decision | Rationale |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| **Sorted bar charts** over choropleth maps | Only 10 countries — precise ranking more useful than geography |\n",
    "| **Metric toggle** (count / loss / users / time) | Avoids chart overload; keeps frequency vs. severity distinction explicit |\n",
    "| **Box plots** for defense outcomes | Distributions are more honest than means for skewed severity data |\n",
    "| **Heatmaps** for cross-category analysis | Compact representation of two-dimensional categorical relationships |\n",
    "| **Section structure** (overview → detail) | Supports both fast management orientation and deeper analyst exploration |\n",
    "| **No causal claims** in annotations | Dataset is synthetic and balanced — findings are described as patterns within the data |\n",
    "| **GitHub Pages deployment** | Reproducible, version-controlled, accessible without installation |\n",
    "\n",
